				 Funds for micro-finance
 OUR CORRESPONDENT				 	 P. Chidambaram in New Delhi on Tuesday. Picture by Ramakant Kushwaha																								New Delhi, Oct. 9: The government will set up two funds of Rs 500 crore each for cheap credit to the poor. 																								Based on the interim report of the financial inclusion committee, we have decided to set up two funds  financial inclusion fund and financial inclusion technology fund  of Rs 500 crore each, said Union finance minister P. Chidambaram. 																								The government will implement the recommendations of the committee chaired by C. Rangarajan, chairman of the economic advisory council to the Prime Minister.																								A Rs 100-crore micro-finance development fund has already been set up by the Centre. 																								The finance minister said the governments role in micro-finance was not clear. It is not yet clear what should the government do, what shouldnt the government do, what should the government regulate and what it shouldnt regulate, he added. 																								The government has introduced a bill in Parliament to regulate non-profit micro-finance institutions. 																								The bill will empower the National Bank for Rural and Agricultural Development (Nabard) to regulate the micro-finance sector. Trusts, societies and co-operatives will come under Nabard, while non-banking finance companies will be kept out of its ambit. 																								According to the bill, the co-operatives, trusts and societies will have to be registered under the Microfinance Development Council, which will be a Nabard-promoted entity. It will allow the institutions to raise savings, but they will have to take approvals from the council. 																								The minimum capital requirement has been fixed at Rs 1 lakh, with promoters contributing at least 50 per cent of the amount. 
